## Summary

When `screenLockInhibitionMethod` is set to `WakeLockSentinel` (non-default), the wake lock is not re-enabled after the window is minimised and restored, even if the user is on a call. As a result the display can sleep mid-call for users on the WakeLockSentinel path.

No open issue currently reports this symptom. The bug is latent: it only fires when both gates align, the non-default config plus a minimise-restore during an active call, which keeps the user-facing incidence low. Filing for completeness and to prevent it biting the next user who opts into the non-default path.

## Location

`app/mainAppWindow/browserWindowManager.js:114`

```js
if (this.screenLockInhibitionMethod === "WakeLockSentinel") {
  this.window.on("restore", this.enableWakeLockOnWindowRestore);
}
```

The handler is registered as an unbound class method. Electron invokes event listeners with `this` set to the `BrowserWindow` instance, so `enableWakeLockOnWindowRestore` at lines 180-184 references `this.isOnCall` and `this.window.webContents.send` against the wrong object. The method silently no-ops.

## Regression source

Commit `c2a458e` in PR #2068 ("Add screen sharing configuration and improve hardware compatibility") removed the `.bind(this)` that had previously been applied at registration. The PR reworked `screenLockInhibitionMethod` wiring and the bind was dropped as collateral. Nothing in the PR description suggests this was intentional. The earlier correct state was introduced in commit `8815875`.

## Fix

One line. Either:

```js
this.window.on("restore", this.enableWakeLockOnWindowRestore.bind(this));
```

or convert `enableWakeLockOnWindowRestore` to an arrow class field so it captures `this` lexically:

```js
enableWakeLockOnWindowRestore = () => {
  if (this.isOnCall) {
    this.window.webContents.send("enable-wakelock");
  }
};
```

The arrow field matches the modern convention used elsewhere in the file.

## Test plan

With `screenLockInhibitionMethod: "WakeLockSentinel"` in config, start a call, minimise and restore the window, and verify the wake lock re-engages (Teams should continue to prevent display sleep).

## Context

Split from the LLM-generated bulk report #2417 (claim A). Claims B and C from that report are already merged via PR #2435. Claim F was verified correct as-is on current Electron. Claims D, E, and G were judged defense-in-depth or theoretical and not worth separate tickets.

### Describe the feature

disable passkey nag/stuck screen on linux

### Motivation

More and more people have issues with passkey functionality which is not supported via electron.

a quick fix from t4l can be to "disable" (overwrite) the credentials capability the browser reports to the app to circumvent passkey.

hint in the config name that this is a nasty hack. and if passkey is required this wont help. but if alternatives are still allowed this should help.

https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/41472

```
import { webFrame } from 'electron';

const blockCredentialsApiCode = `
(() => {
    Object.defineProperty(navigator, 'credentials', {
        value: undefined,
        configurable: true,
        writable: true,
    });
})()`;

webFrame.executeJavaScript(blockCredentialsApiCode).catch((err) => {
    console.error('error when executeJavaScript for blockCredentialsApiCode', err);
});
```

